A. OVERVIEW


This report analyzes the automotive market in Poland, including: passenger
cars, off-road vehicles, and small commercial vehicles.  It describes the
present situation in this market in Poland and indicates major Polish
producers, importers, and foreign suppliers.  Regulations concerning import
of automobiles are presented as well as financing issues.

Poland, with a population of 39 million, is the largest single automotive
market in Central Europe.  In 1993 Poles bought more than 220,000 motor
vehicles, the Czechs and Slovaks bought only 95,000, the Hungarians 34,000,
the Romanians 41,000, while the Bulgarians only 11,000.

U.S. companies are present on the Polish market through two of the big three
U.S. firms - Opel/General Motors and Ford - offering their European models on
the market.  U.S. made models are not very popular due to the differences in
European and the U.S. specifications.  Also, shipping costs are much higher
from the USA than from European Union (EU) countries.  Another factor which
influences the import figures is the availability of authorized service (very
limited for the U.S. models), availability of spare parts, and components,
and, last but not least, the preferential duty rates for European Union
countries, EFTA and CEFTA countries and duty-free quota for European Union
countries.  EU manufacturers benefit from common regulations and standards,
and from a geographic advantage for transportation and support.

Most popular companies in Poland are:  Italian FIAT; German Volkswagen, Opel
and Ford (the latter two recognized in Poland as German, not American);
French Renault, Peugeot, and Citroen; and Japanese Toyota, Mazda, and Honda;
Polish Polonez/FSO.

