C. MARKET ASSESSMENT


Market Demand

The automotive industry in Poland is a relatively big sector with a history
of over 70 years.  The present employment reaches 150,000.  In the 1970s, the
country's seven vehicle manufacturing plants owned by the government produced
over 446,000 vehicles annually, including 360,000 passenger cars.  In the
1980s Polish economy was hit by a recession, which caused the demand for cars
in Poland to fall (in 1985 domestic production of passenger cars was 283,000
units).  The early 1990s brought a significant change: the demand for cars
increased noticeably, and foreign companies began view Poland as a promising
market.  The latter was a result of both the global recession in the
automotive market, and the liberalization of the customs regulations in
Poland.  The situation resulted in deteriorating position for Polish
producers (in 1991 domestic production of passenger cars dropped to 167,000
units).  The neglected national industry stood no chance to face the
challenge from foreign companies who introduced better products and consumer
financing.

The Ministry of Industry and Trade drafted a legislative package to protect
the industry to the year 2002.  The priorities:
- maintain the customs protection of the Polish market
- offer preferences to the national producers and encourage joint-ventures
- restrict the import of used vehicles.

The legislative protection immediately resulted in a significant increase in
domestic production.  The figure for 1992 reached 216,000 units, and for 1993
- 334,000 units, a result not reported for many years.  The protection of
domestic production will last until 2002, but high customs rates will be
gradually decreased to that date.

It is expected that the Polish market will grow steadily over the next few
years.  The forecasts estimate that in the year 1995 it will reach 250,000 of
motor vehicles of all types, hit 300,000 in 1997 and peak in the year 2000
with 350,000 units.

Related to the automotive market in Poland are environmental problems caused
by the industry.  According to members of the environmental protection
commission in the Polish parliament, by July 1995, all cars produced in
Poland or imported into Poland should be fitted with catalatic converters.
The commission has already submitted a draft resolution to the parliament
which will oblige the government to introduce such regulations.  Currently,
because of environmental problems, Polish law prohibits the import of
two-stroke engines.  However, the duty-free car import quota does not
encourage environmental protection.  Out of the 33,500 cars that can be
imported duty- free in 1994 only 8,500 must be "green."  Cars with catalatic
converters are manufactured and sold in Poland. A converter increases the
price of cars by at least $500.  In addition, unleaded gasoline is only 100
Polish zloty ($ 0.005) per liter cheaper than leaded.  The new regulation
will result in increased prices of cars, already very high in Poland.

D. BEST SALES PROSPECTS

According to Polish automotive experts the best sales prospects are:

- for a limited time, relatively cheap cars with basic accessories (not to
exceed the value ECU 7000 with excise tax, the current exchange rate is $1.12
per 1 ECU); for example the Fiat Uno

- over time, the best prospects are more varied:

      medium sized cars with modern safety standards (airbag, ABS, reinforced
doors      with steel bars) and a moderate price;

      cheap, economical city cars;

      vans and commercial vehicles.


E. COMPETITIVE SITUATION


Domestic Production

The Polish market is still dominated by domestic producers, but not to the
extent it was in the 1970s and 1980s, when foreign made cars were rarely seen
on Polish roads.  The market for passenger cars at that time was dominated by
Polish Fiat 125p, small Fiat 126p, and later by the Polonez.  The economic
changes introduced in 1989 enabled Poles to buy other makes.  It is estimated
that about two-third of the cars registered now in Poland are still produced
domestically.

The following are Polish producers and joint ventures in the automotive
sector in Poland:

FSM (Fabryka Samochodow Malolitrazowych - Small Capacity Car Factory) and
FIAT (Fiat Auto Poland)

The biggest single investor in the Polish automotive sector is the Fiat Auto,
whose relations with Poland date back to the 1920s.  Fiat contributed 90
percent of the stock, 145 million ECU.  The State Treasury holds 10 percent,
i.e. 16 million ECU.  Fiat promised to invest more than two billion dollars
in the company, including 1.2 billion dollars to pay back FSM's debt and 850
million as investments over six years.  Currently, the company produces old
small Fiat 126p (60,969 units produced in 1992, figures for 1993 not
available when the report was prepared), Cinquecento with two versions of
engine - 700 ccm and 900 ccm (82,00 units produced in 1992).  The FSM plant
in Tychy will have an ultimate annual production of 230,000 Cinquecento model
vehicles.  Half of the production is being exported.  In 1994 Fiat Auto
Poland launched the assembly of the Uno, which has dominated the Italian
market for 10 years and proved to be the best selling imported car in Poland
for the past two years.  Assembly of Tipo and Punto Fiat models is expected
to follow.

FSO (Fabryka Samochodow Osobowych - Passenger Car Factory) and
General Motors Poland Ltd.

FSO is the producer of the Polonez car.  Polonez is offered in various
models, not only as a passenger car, but also as a pickup, commercial
vehicle, ambulance etc.  The production figures show 54,500 units in 1989,
then a significant drop to only 34,000 units in 1991 - due to liberal customs
tariffs and the competitiveness of imported vehicles.  When the new,
protective regulations were introduced, the production doubled in just one
year to 75,400 in 1992.  Unlike with Cinquecento, the majority of cars
produced in FSO is destined to Polish market, with only small quantities
exported to China and Egypt.  FSO negotiated for three years with General
Motors to establish a joint venture.  The agreement resulted in establishing
General Motor Poland in May 1994.  Assembly of the Opel Astra sedan is
scheduled to begin in fall 1994 with annual production expected to reach
33,000 cars per year (ultimately capacity is 100,000 to 150,000 automobiles).


FSR POLMO (Fabryka Samochodow Rolniczych POLMO - Agricultural Vehicle
Factory) and Volkswagen A.G.

The FSR factory in Poznan established a joint venture with German Volkswagen.
 The German company is expected to invest $79 million in the manufacture of
the T4 delivery van.  Ultimate output will be 20,000 vehicles a year.

FSC (Fabryka Samochodow Ciezarowych w Lublinie - Small Truck Factory in
Lublin) and Peugeot

The factory is well known as the producer of the "Zuk" small delivery van.
It used to produce tires and vehicle parts and components for partners
throughout Poland.  FSC in Lublin, after signing an agreement with French
Peugeot, has just begun assembling of the Peugeot 405, with 2,000 cars a year
as a start (ultimately 10,000 to 35,000 cars a year).  Peugeot hopes to
invest $63 million in 4 years.  The company also plans to modernize the
Polish light truck "Zuk".

WZM (Wojskowe Zaklady Motoryzacyjne w Glownie - Military Auto Plant in
Glowno) and Mercedes

The military auto plant in Glowno near Lodz has begun assembly of Mercedes
308d delivery vans with a capacity of 1.8 tons.  Beginning 1995, 1,000
vehicles a year will roll off the plant's assembly lines.  They also plan to
assemble passenger Mercedes for taxi cabs and ambulances.  These will be the
200D and 250D models.  They will be assembled at a rate 1,500 cars a year.

