Competitive Factors

The Polish market for automobiles is dominated by relatively cheap
small-to-medium- sized cars.  Previously, the price of the car was the
dominant factor influencing buying decisions.  Now safety is becoming
increasingly more important, along with price, fuel consumption, prices of
parts and components, well developed network of authorized service stations.
These changes are possible due to the change in the relationship between car
prices and incomes in Poland.  An average Pole no longer earns $20-$30 a
month, but $300-$400.  This increased the number of potential customers in
the showrooms.

Poles still favor small capacity cars with engines up to 2000 ccm (smaller
capacities, up to 1600 ccm are in biggest favor).  This is due to insurance
rates which vary depending on the size of the engine, and are very high for
bigger cars.  The majority of cars imported to Poland are gasoline cars, not
diesels.  The proportion between these two types is 4:1.

